! DO NOT MERGE - for discussion only !
---
*NOTE: to avoid cluttering this PR all changes are being integrated on branch [infoportugal/experimental](https://github.com/infoportugal/wagtail-modeltranslation/tree/experimental). To try the latest please checkout `experimental`.*

Hi @DiogoMarques29, @rmartins90, @Alexandre27,

After patching some of `wagtail-modeltranslation` issues I've hit a roadblock where fetching saved pages would not yield the correct translated values. I wrote about this on https://github.com/infoportugal/wagtail-modeltranslation/issues/103#issuecomment-352006610 and I also wrote a leaner test illustrating this issue on 1a656b98da4327dedf1d3400640e8d6def710760. 

I believe the root cause is that `Page` translated fields (slug_xx, title_xx, etc) are not in `Page` DB table but in its subclasses. Perhaps this is a `django-modeltranslation` issue but as far as I can see it's not a scenario they explicitly support. So perhaps we are not meant to model our tables this way?

As a POC (and following @cormier work on PR #124) I've re-designed `wagtail-modeltranslation` as having the translated fields living in the `Page` model. This has its caveats I'll address later but so far I find it easier to manage than the current approach of having `Page` translated fields in its subclasses. The current approach *goes against the grain* of both `Wagtail` and `django-modeltranslation` since it forces us to use `.specific` to fetch these fields and it's not a supported scenario by the latter.

### Pros of this change

1. Saves DB queries by avoiding uses of `.specific` to fetch url_path_xx, slug_xx, title_xx, etc (PR #151);
2. Saves DB queries when saving pages' descendants since url_path_xx lives on a single table `Page` instead being spread across multiple subclasses;
3. Works as prescribed by `django-modeltranslation`, thus avoiding the issue illustrated by 1a656b98da4327dedf1d3400640e8d6def710760;
4. Simpler code, on most (perhaps all) patched methods since we can rely exclusively on `Page`, without any need for the subclass;
5. Related to 1.: When building menus on templates we can get the correct title and url without using `.specific()`;
6. Related to 3.: this will make the original django-modeltranslation's `update_translation_fields` command work without any changes.

### Cons brought by this change

1. The big one: this will change wagtailcore `Page` table. To avoid conflicts with wagtail own migrations we need to do this silently (and hope they will never add slug_xx, title_xx, etc columns of their own);
    - Mitigated by our own override to `makemigrations` that deletes any `wagtailcore` migrations before they are saved to file, and `sync_page_translation_fields` that creates the necessary translation columns in Page table. While this solution is not perfect it makes the use of `wagtail-modeltranslation` as seamless as possible for the user.
2. `slugurl` tag will cease to work, even by patching SlugField's `pre_save()`, when language is not the default one;
    - `slugurl_trans` was created to replace `slugurl`. By default it accepts the slug in the default language but it's also possible to use a slug in a different language by adding the language as the second argument;
3. Last but not least, this brings breaking changes to `wagtail-modeltranslation` and at this point I don't have a migration script/ strategy though I don't think it would to be too difficult.

All things considered I believe this is the best path for `wagtail-modeltranslation` and even the breaking changes are worth it.

Let me know your thoughts. I'm open to suggestions and criticism and I'm happy to make changes to accommodate your feedback.

@Erwhann-Rouge, @WnP, @helmantel I've noticed your recent PRs and I would like to hear your opinion about this.

Thanks and Merry Xmas

*PS: currently Travis is breaking for some Wagtail versions, once PR https://github.com/deschler/django-modeltranslation/pull/431 is released those should pass.*

